vectorData.altText: 18. Region A is supplied by the __________ ____________artery.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.
Thatâ€™s right! The body (genu and rostrum) of the corpus callosum, A is supplied by penetrating branches of the anterior cerebral artery (ACA).

Read the following with reference to the figure provided.
You know that the anterior cerebral arteries and their branches, the callosomarginal and pericallosal arteries, supply the medial surfaces of the frontal and parietal lobes, as well as the adjacent cortex of the superolateral surface. Penetrating branches arise from the ACAs and anterior communicating artery to supply much of the corpus callosum, as well as the inferior portion of the head of the caudate nucleus. 
In your mind, include these structures in the ACA territory.
